The paper discusses bibliometrics, scientometrics, informetrics, and webometrics, which are all related to information retrieval (cs.IR) and digital libraries (cs.DL). The study also explores the cognitive and social distinctness of iMetrics with respect to general information science (IS), which could fall under social and information sciences (cs.SI). Additionally, the paper mentions a shared vocabulary and literature/knowledge base, which could relate to cybernetics (cs.CY) and systems and control (cs.SD).
